"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 2 Samuel chapters 4–7
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-2samuel-4-7.py

Ch4: End of rival kingship — shadow of Christ's innocent advance to universal throne
Ch5: David anointed over all Israel; capture of Zion — type of Christ's universal kingship
Ch6: Ark brought to Jerusalem; David's priestly kingship — theme of divine presence
Ch7: The Davidic Covenant — the OT's central messianic oracle; direct NT citations in
     Heb 1:5 (v14), Acts 13:22-23 (v8,12), Luke 1:32-33 (v12-16), 2 Sam 7:12-16 = the
     messianic promise that all subsequent OT messianism builds upon

Christological classifications used:
- Ch4: shadow (David's advance without bloodguilt), theme (righteousness of the king)
- Ch5 v2: type (shepherd-king); v4: shadow (thirty years old); v7: type (Zion as Christ's seat)
- Ch6: theme (divine presence brings blessing), type (priestly-kingly worship)
- Ch7 v12-16: direct prophecy (NT explicitly cites as fulfilled in Christ)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

SAMUEL2 = {
  "4": {
    "1": "<p>As a shadow: the collapse of Ishbosheth's courage when Abner dies — 'his courage failed him, and all Israel was dismayed' — illustrates the fragility of kingship that rests on human power rather than divine appointment. The rival king survives only because of his general's support; with Abner gone, the house of Saul disintegrates. This pattern prefigures the collapse of all human rival claims before the Davidic heir: the kingdoms of this world become the kingdom of the LORD (Rev 11:15). David does not need to campaign against Ishbosheth; the rival throne falls by its own structural weakness.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Beerothite commanders Baanah and Rechab are introduced as agents who believe they serve the Davidic cause by eliminating the rival king. The revelation that follows is critical: David repudiates their logic entirely. Their assumption that the king's advance requires violence against his enemies is false — the true king's advance is secured by YHWH, not by assassination. This shadow-pattern is fulfilled in Christ's complete abstention from political violence in his advance to the throne (John 18:36: 'my kingdom is not of this world, or my servants would fight').</p>",
    "3": "<p>The note about the Beerothites having fled to Gittaim is a sociological aside — displaced peoples absorbed into the land. It reflects the theme of the mixed community that characterizes the Davidic kingdom: Jebusites, Beerothites, Gittites (Obed-edom in ch 6), Philistine mercenaries (the Cherethites and Pelethites) — all present under David's administration. The Davidic kingdom as an inclusive polity prefigures the nature of Christ's kingdom as one that gathers from all peoples (Rev 7:9).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The mention of Mephibosheth son of Jonathan — 'lame in both feet,' dropped by his nurse when the news came from Jezreel — is structurally placed here as a foreshadowing of ch 9. Though Mephibosheth plays no role in ch 4, his introduction immediately before the narrative of his grandfather Saul's last male heir (Ishbosheth) being killed anticipates the Davidic question: what will happen to the house of Jonathan? The answer in ch 9 — David seeking him out for ḥesed — is a type of Christ's seeking of the helpless, those who cannot walk in their own strength, to bring them to the king's table.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Rechab and Baanah enter Ishbosheth's house 'during the heat of the day' — the standard notation for midday rest when security would be relaxed. The pretext of 'getting wheat' is a domestic deception. The entire episode illustrates how the end of rival power comes not through heroic battle but through betrayal and treachery — which David will explicitly condemn. The Davidic king's response distinguishes the kingdom of God from worldly kingdoms that routinely benefit from assassinations they disavow.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The murder of Ishbosheth on his bed signals his complete vulnerability. As a shadow: the innocent suffer under the actions of those who imagine they serve the true king through violence. The narrative of God's kingdom advancing through betrayal and unjust suffering is deepened and inverted in Christ: where Ishbosheth's murder removes a false claimant, Christ's murder removes the true king from the world's view — but the resurrection vindicates what the cross appeared to destroy.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Rechab and Baanah take Ishbosheth's head to David at Hebron — presenting what they believe is a trophy of service to the true king. The pattern: those who think they advance God's kingdom through violent means against its enemies. David's response will establish the proper norm. As a theme: the willingness to use ungodly means to achieve supposedly godly ends is condemned throughout Scripture (Rom 3:8: 'let us do evil that good may come').</p>",
    "8": "<p>The assassins' claim — 'The LORD has given your enemies into your hands' — invokes YHWH as the justification for their act. This is the most theologically significant moment in the chapter: they have murdered Saul's son and credit YHWH. David's response refutes the claim that YHWH operates through political assassination. As a theme, this prefigures the consistent NT insistence that the advance of God's kingdom does not operate through worldly violence or manipulation (2 Cor 10:3-4: 'the weapons of our warfare are not of the flesh').</p>",
    "9": "<p>David's oath formula — 'As the LORD lives, who has redeemed my life out of every adversity' — is a statement of covenantal trust in YHWH as David's redeemer (<em>podheh</em>, the same root as kinsman-redeemer). David attributes his preservation not to the elimination of his enemies but to YHWH's active deliverance. This is the theology of the 'redemption of life' that culminates in Christ's redemptive work: 'he gave his life as a ransom for many' (Matt 20:28) — YHWH as the ultimate redeemer.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David recalls the Amalekite messenger of 2 Sam 1 — executed for claiming to have killed Saul and bringing the crown. Now two men have committed actual murder and expect reward. David's consistency — refusing to benefit from assassinations of those in the house of Saul — establishes a principle of the king's righteousness: the true king does not advance through the blood of rivals. This shadow-pattern reaches its fulfillment in Christ who, being 'king of kings,' did not use his power to eliminate opposition but absorbed the violence of his enemies onto himself.</p>",
    "11": "<p>David's judicial reasoning: 'How much more should I not require his blood at your hand and rid the earth of you, when wicked men have killed a righteous man in his own house on his bed?' The logic escalates: if condemning a man who killed Saul-at-Saul's-own-request, how much more condemning those who murdered an innocent man. The theme of the innocent man murdered in his own house, with the king's justice demanding retribution, is a shadow of the NT's theology that Christ's death — the murder of the truly righteous one — demands divine retributive response (Acts 2:23-24: 'you put him to death, but God raised him').</p>",
    "12": "<p>The execution of the assassins and the display of their bodies at the pool in Hebron (<em>al bᵉrēḵat ḥeḇrôn</em>) is public justice — the king's visible repudiation of assassination as a tool of political advance. Ishbosheth's head is honorably buried in Abner's tomb. As a theme: the Davidic king's commitment to justice that extends even to his enemies — a pattern fulfilled in Christ's prayer from the cross ('Father, forgive them,' Luke 23:34) and in Paul's instruction to repay evil with good (Rom 12:17-21).</p>"
  },
  "5": {
    "1": "<p>The covenant language of ch 5:1 — 'we are your own bone and flesh' (<em>ʿaṣmᵉḵā ûḇᵉśārᵉḵā ʾᵃnaḥnû</em>) — is the kinship formula of covenant union (Gen 2:23: Adam's 'bone of my bones and flesh of my flesh'). The tribes of Israel claim kinship with David as the basis for their submission. This language is taken up by Paul in Eph 5:30 for the believer's union with Christ: 'we are members of his body.' The people's covenantal bonding to the Davidic king is a type of the church's union with Christ — the kinship declared by the tribes is the same kinship that the NT declares to be constituted by the incarnation (Heb 2:14: 'since the children share in flesh and blood, he himself likewise partook of the same things').</p>",
    "2": "<p>The tribal leaders' appeal includes a direct prophetic citation: 'the LORD said to you, you shall shepherd my people Israel, and you shall be ruler over Israel.' The verb 'shepherd' (<em>rāʿāh</em>, to pasture/lead a flock) is the consistent OT metaphor for royal leadership (Ps 78:70-72; Ezek 34:23). This specific oracle about David's shepherd-kingship is what Jesus claims in John 10:11-14 ('I am the good shepherd') and what Ezek 34:23-24 explicitly messianic-izes: 'I will set up over them one shepherd, my servant David, and he shall feed them.' The anointing of David as shepherd-king at Hebron is the OT narrative embodiment of what the NT presents as fulfilled in Christ's universal shepherding.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The covenant David makes with the elders of Israel at Hebron — '<em>wayyikrot dāwiḏ lāhem bᵉrît bᵉḥeḇrôn lipnê YHWH</em>' — is the third and final anointing: the first was private (1 Sam 16:13), the second tribal (2 Sam 2:4), and this one is national. A covenant sealed before YHWH creates the formal, legally binding relationship between king and people. The typological chain points to the new covenant ratified by Christ's blood (Luke 22:20: 'this cup is the new covenant in my blood'), in which Christ as the Davidic heir establishes the binding relationship between himself and the new-covenant community.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The chronological note — 'David was thirty years old when he became king' — has been noticed by readers since the early church as an alignment with Luke 3:23: 'Jesus was about thirty years old when he began his ministry.' Luke may be deliberately invoking the Davidic parallel: the true heir of David begins his public work at the same age his type began to reign. The 'thirty years' marker thus functions as a shadow-pointer within Luke's chronological framing of Jesus's ministry as the fulfillment of Davidic kingship.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The summary of David's reigns — seven and a half years in Hebron, thirty-three in Jerusalem — totaling forty years establishes the forty-year reign as the OT's paradigmatic royal generation (cf. Solomon's forty years, 1 Kgs 11:42). The number forty in OT idiom marks a complete period of trial and fulfillment (forty years wilderness, forty days of Moses on Sinai, forty years of peace under the judges). David's forty-year reign is the type of the 'forever' kingdom: forty years that the NT presents as the temporal shadow of the eternal reign (Rev 11:15).</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Jebusites' taunt — 'you will not come in here; the blind and the lame will drive you away' — is enigmatic. Whatever its precise meaning, David captures the city. As a shadow: the stronghold held by those who mock the king's approach is taken by the king. The city that seemed impregnable is taken — the NT consistently uses this pattern for Christ's conquest: 'the gates of Hades will not prevail' (Matt 16:18); the 'strong man's house' is ransacked (Matt 12:29).</p>",
    "7": "<p>A type: 'David captured the stronghold of Zion, which is now the city of David.' Zion becomes the city of the Davidic king — and through the Psalter and the prophets, the seat of the eternal king and the place of eschatological gathering. Ps 2:6 ('I have set my king on Zion, my holy hill') is the OT locus for this typology; Heb 12:22 ('you have come to Mount Zion') and Rev 14:1 ('I looked, and behold, on Mount Zion stood the Lamb') make explicit that Zion as the seat of the Davidic king is fulfilled in Christ's heavenly kingship.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The enigmatic reference to the 'water tunnel' (<em>ṣinnôr</em>) and the 'blind and lame' is difficult historically but important typologically. Whatever the military tactic, the point is that the apparently inaccessible is accessed by the king who is determined to take the city. As a theme: Christ's approach to what human blindness declares inaccessible — the entry into human suffering and death — takes the stronghold by a route that the proud and powerful consider beneath contempt.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David settles in the stronghold and 'built up the city all around from the Millo inward.' The building program is the founding act of kingship: the king makes the city his own by inhabiting and improving it. As a type: Christ's 'building' program is the church — 'I will build my church' (Matt 16:18) — and his inhabiting of Jerusalem is fulfilled in the heavenly Jerusalem he prepares as his dwelling (John 14:2-3; Rev 21:2-3).</p>",
    "10": "<p>The theological summary: 'David grew steadily greater, for the LORD God of hosts was with him.' The phrase 'the LORD God of hosts was with him' (<em>YHWH ʾĕlōhê ṣᵉḇāʾôt ʿimmô</em>) is the OT's most concentrated version of the Immanuel promise — 'God with us.' The pattern of the king's greatness being entirely attributed to divine presence is the OT foundation for the NT's claim about Christ: 'God was with him' (Acts 10:38). As a theme: the Davidic king who grows in strength precisely because YHWH is with him prefigures the one in whom YHWH is not merely present with but is personally.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Hiram king of Tyre sends cedar timber and craftsmen to build David a palace. The Gentile king of the great Phoenician trading city places his resources at the Israelite king's disposal — a shadow of the eschatological vision in Isa 60:5-7, where the nations bring their wealth to Zion. The inclusion of Gentile resources in building the Davidic capital prefigures the NT vision of the nations being incorporated into the kingdom (Eph 2:11-22).</p>",
    "12": "<p>David's recognition — 'the LORD had established him as king over Israel and had elevated his kingdom for the sake of his people Israel' — is a statement of divine appointment for communal benefit. The king is established not for his own glory but 'for the sake of his people.' This pattern is the OT template for the NT's description of Christ's Davidic kingship: he does not seek the throne for himself but is exalted by the Father 'for us and for our salvation' (Nicene Creed; Phil 2:9-11).</p>",
    "13": "<p>The brief notice that David took more wives and concubines in Jerusalem reflects the ANE practice of royal polygamy as political alliance-building. The narrative does not endorse this practice; it notes it as fact within David's reign. As a shadow pointing to the need for a better king: where David multiplies wives, the Deuteronomic law for kings explicitly prohibits it (Deut 17:17). The king 'after God's own heart' nonetheless fails to fully embody the royal ideal — a recurring shadow establishing the necessity of a sinless fulfillment.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The list of sons born in Jerusalem begins with Nathan — whose name will be associated with the Lukan genealogy of Jesus (Luke 3:31 traces the line through Nathan, not Solomon). This alternative Davidic descent line through Nathan rather than Solomon is the genealogical foundation for the line from which Mary descends, ensuring that the incarnate Christ is biologically Davidic through Mary while legally royal-Davidic through Joseph. The son Nathan is a genealogical shadow in the middle of the list.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The continuation of the son list — Ibhar, Elishua, Nepheg, Japhia — is a record of the Davidic household at the height of its power in Jerusalem. As a theme: the multiplication of the Davidic line in Jerusalem is the OT's expression of covenant fruitfulness — 'your offspring shall be as the stars of heaven' — and finds its NT realization in the spiritual multiplication of those who become 'children of God' through Christ (John 1:12; Rom 8:17).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The completion of the Jerusalem son list: Elishama, Eliada, Eliphelet. This genealogical record of the Davidic household is not spiritually empty: genealogy in the OT is the structure through which God's covenant promises are tracked and transmitted. Every son listed is potentially in the line through which the promise of 2 Sam 7:12 will be fulfilled. The list establishes the fertility and continuity of the Davidic house as the vehicle for covenant purposes.</p>",
    "17": "<p>When the Philistines hear that David has been anointed over all Israel, they come up in force 'to search for him.' The new king is immediately threatened by the dominant military power. The pattern: the anointed king's enthronement immediately provokes the attack of the enemy. This is the Ps 2:1-3 pattern ('why do the nations rage... the kings of the earth set themselves against the LORD and against his anointed?'), fulfilled in the opposition Christ faces immediately after his messianic identity is established (Matt 2:3-16; Rev 12:1-6).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The Valley of Rephaim (<em>ʿēmeq rᵉpāʾîm</em>) — named for the Rephaim, the ancient 'giant' peoples of pre-Israelite Canaan — is the Philistine deployment zone. The choice of location by the Philistines invokes the memory of the pre-conquest inhabitants whom Israel was commanded to dispossess. The enemies of the Davidic king thus stand in the long lineage of those who oppose the divine claim on the land — a typological chain culminating in the NT's 'principalities and powers' who oppose Christ's kingdom (Eph 6:12).</p>",
    "19": "<p>David 'inquired of the LORD' before engaging the Philistines. This pattern of prophetic consultation (<em>šāʾal bYHWH</em>) before each battle is the defining characteristic of Davidic warfare — in contrast to Saul, whose failures were characterized by acting without prophetic authorization. As a theme: the king who acts only in dependence on YHWH's word is the OT pattern for Christ's 'I can do nothing on my own' (John 5:30) and 'I do nothing from myself, but speak just as the Father taught me' (John 8:28).</p>",
    "20": "<p>The victory at Baal-perazim — named 'Lord of the breach' after the breakthrough — elicits David's theological interpretation: 'The LORD has burst through my enemies before me like a bursting flood.' The verb <em>pāraṣ</em> (to break through, to burst) is used for YHWH's sudden, overwhelming intervention. As a revelation of God: YHWH as the one who 'breaks through' on behalf of his anointed establishes the pattern of divine irruption that the NT presents as fulfilled in Christ's resurrection — God breaking through the barrier of death on behalf of his Son (Acts 2:24).</p>",
    "21": "<p>The Philistines abandon their idols, which David and his men take away. The idols abandoned by the defeated enemy are captured by the victorious king — a reversal of the Ark's capture in 1 Sam 4-5. As a theme: the true king's victory results in the stripping of power from false gods (Col 2:15: 'he disarmed the rulers and authorities and put them to open shame, triumphing over them in him'). The Philistine idols left on the battlefield at Baal-perazim are a small-scale version of the disarming of 'every rule and authority and power' that 1 Cor 15:24 assigns to the Davidic Son at the end.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The Philistines return to the Valley of Rephaim — the same enemy, the same territory. The necessity of a second engagement reinforces that the king's victory over opposition is not a single event but a sustained campaign. As a theme: the warfare of the Davidic king is ongoing, not resolved by a single battle. The NT presents the same pattern for Christ's kingdom: 'he must reign until he has put all his enemies under his feet' (1 Cor 15:25), a present-tense ongoing process, not a completed act.</p>",
    "23": "<p>For the second battle, YHWH gives a different strategy: 'do not go straight up; circle around behind them and come at them in front of the balsam trees.' The command to attack from an unexpected direction — not the direct assault but the flanking movement — illustrates that the king who obeys YHWH receives specific guidance for each engagement rather than a general formula. As a theme: Christ's strategies in the NT are similarly non-conventional — feeding rather than fighting (John 6:35), forgiving rather than condemning (John 8:11), dying rather than escaping.</p>",
    "24": "<p>The signal for attack: 'when you hear the sound of marching in the tops of the balsam trees, rouse yourself to act, for then the LORD has gone out before you to strike the Philistine army.' YHWH himself is the advance guard; the king's action follows YHWH's initiative. As a revelation of God: the LORD 'goes out before' his anointed into battle — the divine warrior who leads the army. This prefigures Rev 19:11-16, where Christ the warrior-king on the white horse goes out 'to judge and make war,' and the armies of heaven follow him.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David's obedience — 'he did as the LORD commanded him' — and the result: the Philistines struck from Geba to Gezer. The formula 'just as the LORD commanded' marks the completion of the obedience-victory cycle. As a type: the Davidic king who hears, obeys, and sees victory is the OT template for Christ's obedience: 'he became obedient to the point of death, even death on a cross. Therefore God has highly exalted him' (Phil 2:8-9). The obedience of the son is the mechanism of the victory.</p>"
  },
  "6": {
    "1": "<p>David assembles thirty thousand chosen men for the procession — a massive demonstration of the national significance of this event. The ark of YHWH is not being moved as a religious act only; it is a national-political event of the highest order. As a theme: the bringing of YHWH's presence into the capital city is the defining act of the Davidic kingdom — the moment when the seat of divine presence and the seat of royal power are united in Jerusalem. The NT fulfillment is the incarnation, where divine presence and royal power are united not in a city but in a person (John 1:14: the Word 'tabernacled among us').</p>",
    "2": "<p>The ark is described as 'called by the name of YHWH of armies who is enthroned between the cherubim' — the ark as YHWH's throne and dwelling-place. The theology of divine presence concentrated in the ark is foundational for the Temple theology that follows. As a type: the ark as the localized presence of YHWH in Israel's midst prefigures the incarnate Christ — both are the physical, tangible locus of divine presence in the world. As John 2:21 makes explicit, 'he was speaking about the temple of his body.'</p>",
    "3": "<p>The placement of the ark on a new cart — a well-intentioned but incorrect procedure — anticipates the disaster of v.6-7. The Mosaic law specified that the ark must be carried on poles by Levites (Num 4:15; 7:9), never on a cart. The Philistines had transported it on a cart (1 Sam 6:7-11) — David is imitating Philistine procedure rather than Mosaic law. As a shadow: good intentions do not sanctify wrong method; the presence of God is approached on his own terms, not human convenience. The NT echoes this in John 4:24 ('God is spirit, and those who worship him must worship in spirit and truth').</p>",
    "4": "<p>The cart carries the ark while Ahio walks in front. The delegation of the physical transport to a cart rather than Levites reflects the failure to follow the Torah carefully. As a theme: the gap between reverence for YHWH's presence and precision in the manner of approach is the OT ground for the NT's insistence on Christ as the one designated 'way' — the only specified approach to the Father (John 14:6). The casual replication of Philistine procedure with the ark is a permanent warning against assuming that sincere worship validates incorrect form.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The celebration 'with all kinds of instruments' before the ark is joyful and genuine. The whole house of Israel participates. As a theme: the worship that accompanies the presence of YHWH is communal, full-bodied, and exuberant — it engages the whole people and the whole person. The NT parallel is the worship of the Lamb in Rev 5:9-14, where 'every creature in heaven and on earth' sings before the one in whom divine presence is fully embodied.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Uzzah reaches out to steady the ark when the oxen stumble. The act appears instinctive and protective — he is trying to prevent the ark from falling. Yet YHWH's anger 'flared against Uzzah, and God struck him down.' As a theme: the holiness of divine presence cannot be managed by human instinct, even well-meant instinct. The holiness of YHWH is not a problem to be solved by the reach of human hands. This is the OT's most acute statement of the distance between the holy God and fallen humanity — a distance resolved only in the incarnation, where God himself bridges it by becoming approachable in human form (Heb 4:16: 'let us draw near with confidence').</p>",
    "7": "<p>Uzzah's death 'for his irreverence' (<em>ʿal-haššal</em>, for the fault/rashness) is the irreducible theological datum: YHWH is holy, and the holiness of his presence demands the specific approach he has prescribed. The death of Uzzah is not arbitrary but reflects the OT's consistent theology that YHWH's presence kills those who approach wrongly (Lev 10:1-3; Num 4:15; 1 Sam 6:19). The NT resolution is not to diminish the holiness but to provide the designated mediator: Christ as the one who makes the holy approachable (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 7:25).</p>",
    "8": "<p>David's anger and distress at the LORD for striking Uzzah — the place named 'Perez-uzzah' ('breaking of Uzzah') — is a genuine human response to an encounter with holy power that exceeds comprehension. As a theme: the gap between human expectation and divine holiness produces fear and confusion. The NT name for this resolution is 'grace and truth' — the fullness of YHWH that came through Jesus Christ (John 1:17), in whom the holy presence becomes not a killing force but a saving encounter.</p>",
    "9": "<p>David's question — 'How can the ark of the LORD come to me now?' — is the question of a man confronted with the insurmountable distance between himself and YHWH's holiness. It echoes Peter's 'depart from me, for I am a sinful man, O Lord' (Luke 5:8) — the recognition of unworthiness before divine holiness. As a theme: the human recognition of distance from God is the OT preparation for the NT's answer: the one who bridges the distance is not human effort but the incarnate Son.</p>",
    "10": "<p>David diverts the ark to the house of Obed-edom the Gittite — a foreigner from Gath (the Philistine city). A Philistine from Gath hosts the ark of YHWH. As a shadow of Gentile inclusion: the presence of YHWH that rested with Israel is willingly received and housed by a Gentile, who is abundantly blessed for it. This anticipates the NT's Gentile mission: 'the gospel to the Gentile first' (Rom 1:16 in reverse order) — the presence of YHWH dwelling among those outside the covenant community.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The LORD blesses the household of Obed-edom and 'everything belonging to him' during the three months the ark rests there. As a theme: proximity to the divine presence brings comprehensive blessing — not just spiritual but material and relational ('everything belonging to him'). This is the OT basis for the NT's 'every spiritual blessing in Christ' (Eph 1:3) and the fruitfulness that comes from 'abiding in the vine' (John 15:5). The blessing radiates from the dwelling of divine presence.</p>",
    "12": "<p>When David hears of the blessing on Obed-edom's household, he is moved to bring the ark to the city of David. The logic is significant: the blessing of the Gentile household confirms that the ark belongs in the Davidic capital. As a revelation of God: YHWH blesses whomever he chooses to dwell among — and his dwelling enriches. The NT theology of the Spirit's presence as the source of the church's fruitfulness ('the fruit of the Spirit,' Gal 5:22-23) is the eschatological fulfillment of this blessing pattern.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Six paces into the procession, David sacrifices an ox and a fattened calf — an act of worship at the very commencement of the ark's journey. The offering at the outset, not merely at the destination, establishes that worship accompanies every step of the divine presence's movement, not only its final installation. As a theme: the life of the community that walks with YHWH is punctuated throughout by sacrifice and worship, not only at sacred destinations.</p>",
    "14": "<p>David dances before the LORD 'with all his strength' wearing a linen ephod. The ephod is a priestly garment (Exod 28:4-6); David dresses as a priest to lead the procession of the ark. This priestly-royal gesture is one of the OT's most explicit prefigurations of the Melchizedekian office: the king who also serves as priest before YHWH. Ps 110:4 ('you are a priest forever after the order of Melchizedek') and Heb 7:1-17 identify Christ as the one who permanently unites both offices — something David shadows but Saul was explicitly prohibited from doing (1 Sam 13:8-14).</p>",
    "15": "<p>The whole procession enters Jerusalem with 'shouting and the sound of the trumpet.' The trumpet-blast (<em>šôpār</em>) is the announcement of a royal entry and a sacred assembly. As a type: the royal entry with shouting and trumpet is the OT pattern for the messianic entry. Matt 21:9 ('Hosanna to the Son of David!') fulfills the pattern of jubilant welcome for the Davidic king entering his city — and 1 Thess 4:16 applies the same trumpet imagery to Christ's eschatological return as king.</p>",
    "16": "<p>As the ark enters the city of David, Michal watches from a window and 'despises him in her heart' (<em>wattiḇez lô bilibbāh</em>). The despising of the king who humbles himself in worship before YHWH is the OT's sharpest picture of pride's rejection of the humble king. As a type: the rejection and contempt of those who are offended by the king's self-abasement prefigures the scandal of the cross — 'a stumbling block to Jews and folly to Gentiles' (1 Cor 1:23). Those who expect a king who maintains dignity reject the king who strips it away to dance before YHWH.</p>",
    "17": "<p>The ark is set in the tent David has pitched for it — a new tent in Jerusalem, not the old Mosaic tabernacle at Gibeon. The multiplication of sacred dwelling-places (tabernacle at Gibeon, David's tent in Jerusalem, eventually Solomon's temple) tracks the progressive movement of divine presence toward its ultimate dwelling. As a type: the 'tent' David pitches for YHWH's presence in Jerusalem is a shadow of John 1:14 — 'the Word became flesh and tented among us' — the definitive dwelling of divine presence among human beings.</p>",
    "18": "<p>David offers burnt offerings and fellowship offerings, then 'blessed the people in the name of the LORD.' The priestly-royal act of blessing the people — in the name of YHWH — is the Davidic fulfillment of Aaron's blessing in Num 6:24-26. As a type: the king who blesses the people in YHWH's name prefigures Christ, who 'lifted up his hands and blessed' his disciples at the ascension (Luke 24:50), and who is the mediator of the Aaronic blessing in its fullest form (Heb 13:20-21).</p>",
    "19": "<p>The distribution to the whole assembly — bread, a portion of roasted meat, a cake of raisins — encompasses 'men and women alike' (<em>לְכָל-הָעָם לְכָל-הֲמוֹן יִשְׂרָאֵל לְמֵאִישׁ וְעַד-אִשָּׁה</em>). The king distributes food to the entire people without distinction. As a type: the king's feeding of the gathered people is the OT pattern for Christ's feeding of the multitudes (Mark 6:41-44; John 6:11) and for the eucharistic distribution to all who come to the table. 'All the people went to their homes' is the benediction of the feast.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Michal's cutting sarcasm — 'how the king of Israel has distinguished himself today, going around half-naked in the sight of the slave girls of his servants as any vulgar fellow would' — attacks David for undignified worship. The charge: that genuine, undignified worship before YHWH is unseemly for a king. As a theme: Michal's contempt is the perennial response of those who value royal dignity over authentic worship — the same spirit that 'murmured' at the woman's costly offering to Jesus (Mark 14:4-5).</p>",
    "21": "<p>David's defense of his worship: 'It was before the LORD, who chose me rather than your father and his household, to appoint me as ruler over Israel, the people of the LORD.' The worship is directed to YHWH, not to the audience. The king's dignity before human observers is irrelevant compared to his humility before YHWH. As a theme: Christ's own 'undignified' acts — washing disciples' feet (John 13:5), receiving tax collectors and sinners (Luke 15:2) — are repeatedly attacked for the same reason and defended by the same logic: they are 'before the LORD.'</p>",
    "22": "<p>David's declaration: 'I will make myself yet more contemptible than this, and I will be humble in my own eyes' (<em>wᵉhāyîtî šāpāl bᵉʿênāy</em>) — the king who chooses self-abasement before YHWH over self-presentation before the crowd. This is the OT's clearest anticipation of Phil 2:7-8: 'he emptied himself, taking the form of a servant... he humbled himself by becoming obedient to the point of death.' The Davidic king's willingness to be contemptible in his own sight before YHWH is the precise shadow-pattern of the Son's kenosis.</p>",
    "23": "<p>The judgment on Michal — barrenness to the day of her death — is the narrative's final word on the house of Saul's end: no children, no continuation. The line of Saul (via Michal) does not continue. As a shadow: the old order — the Saulide kingship that was withdrawn — yields no fruit; it ends in barrenness. The Davidic line continues; the Saulide line is barren. This is the OT counterpart to John 15:6 ('whoever does not abide in me is thrown away like a branch and withers') — the branch that is cut off yields nothing.</p>"
  },
  "7": {
    "1": "<p>The chapter opens with 'rest' (<em>hannîaḥ-lô YHWH missāḇîḇ mikkol-ʾōyᵉḇāyw</em>, 'the LORD had given him rest from all his enemies on every side') — the Sabbath-rest of the completed conquest. Hebrews 4:1-11 builds its theology of 'entering God's rest' on this exact vocabulary: the <em>mᵉnûḥāh</em> (rest) promised and partially realized in the Davidic kingdom is the OT type of the eschatological rest that Christ provides. David's rest 'from all his enemies' is a temporal shadow; Heb 4:10 points to the rest 'from his works' that the people of God still enter through faith in Christ.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David's impulse to build YHWH a house is well-intentioned: the king lives in cedar; the ark dwells in a tent. The disparity troubles him. As a theme: the human desire to provide worthy habitation for YHWH is genuine worship-impulse, but YHWH redirects it. The pattern — human initiative towards YHWH redirected by YHWH's counter-initiative — runs through the OT: Abraham offers Ishmael, YHWH provides Isaac; Moses builds the tabernacle, YHWH inhabits it. The greatest instance is Christ: human religion reaches toward God, but the decisive act is God descending to humanity (John 1:14).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Nathan's initial encouragement — 'go ahead and do all that is in your heart, for the LORD is with you' — is retracted by YHWH the same night. Even the prophet's immediate assent to the king's plan can be overridden by YHWH's contrary word. As a theme: genuine prophetic guidance does not consist in affirming the king's existing impulses but in faithfully transmitting YHWH's word even when it contradicts expectations. Nathan's willingness to correct himself in v.4-17 is the mark of true prophecy (Jer 23:16-22).</p>",
    "4": "<p>The word of YHWH comes to Nathan 'that night' — the same night Nathan had given permission. The immediacy of the divine correction establishes the dynamic of the chapter: human plans are subordinated to divine initiative, and the divine counter-plan exceeds the human plan in every dimension. As a revelation of God: YHWH does not merely give guidance when asked; he initiates, corrects, and surprises his servants with a larger vision than they had imagined.</p>",
    "5": "<p>YHWH's rhetorical question — 'are you the one to build me a house to dwell in?' — redirects the initiative from David to YHWH. The emphasis is not that a house should not be built (Solomon will build it) but that YHWH himself initiates the promise of a house rather than receiving one. The counter-question is: not 'will you build me a house?' but 'I will build you a house' (v.11). The divine initiative reverses the human direction of the gift entirely. The NT makes this reversal explicit: 'in this is love, not that we have loved God but that he loved us' (1 John 4:10).</p>",
    "6": "<p>YHWH's autobiography — 'I have not lived in a house since the day I brought Israel up from Egypt until today, but have moved about in a tent' — establishes that divine presence has never been bound to human architecture. The tabernacle is not a constraint but a provision YHWH himself authorized. As a revelation of God: the God who moves with his people in a tent is a God whose presence cannot be architecturally captured — a point Stephen makes in Acts 7:48-50 and that Jesus extends in John 4:21-24 ('neither on this mountain nor in Jerusalem will you worship the Father').</p>",
    "7": "<p>YHWH's question to the tribal leaders — 'why have you not built me a house of cedar?' — reveals that the absence of a permanent temple was not a failure but a chosen pattern: YHWH had not demanded a house. The oracle establishes that the temple is YHWH's initiative (through Solomon), not a human gift to YHWH that earns divine favor. As a theme: the entire system of worship that culminates in the Temple is divinely initiated and prescribed, not humanly invented — which is why Heb 8:5 calls the earthly tabernacle a 'copy and shadow of the heavenly things.'</p>",
    "8": "<p>YHWH's autobiographical report to David — 'I took you from the pasture, from following the sheep, to be ruler over my people Israel' — states the elective pattern directly: the shepherd elevated to king by divine initiative, not human merit. Acts 13:22 cites the same logic: 'I have found in David the son of Jesse a man after my heart, who will do all my will.' The pattern — shepherd elected as ruler — is the OT type that Luke applies to Jesus (Luke 2:8-16: the announcement to shepherds; John 10:11: 'I am the good shepherd' claiming the shepherd-king title).</p>",
    "9": "<p>YHWH's record of accompaniment: 'I have been with you wherever you went, and have cut off all your enemies from before you.' The divine accompaniment is the source of all David's victories — not David's own skill or force. 'I have been with you' is the definitive form of the Immanuel promise at the personal level. As a revelation of God: YHWH's presence with his anointed is the mechanism of his advance — and the NT makes this the framework for Christ: 'God was with him' (Acts 10:38), the pre-crucifixion summary of his ministry.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The promise to plant Israel in a place of their own — 'so that they may live in their own place and be disturbed no more; violent men will not oppress them anymore as before' — is the land-rest promise in its social dimension: security from oppression. This promise was not fully realized in Solomon's reign (1 Kgs 12 shows the people's oppression) and has never been fully realized in Israel's history. As a direct prophecy partially fulfilled: the NT presents the complete realization of this rest-and-security promise in the new creation (Rev 21:4: 'he will wipe away every tear; there will be no more pain').</p>",
    "11": "<p>The transition: 'I will give you rest from all your enemies' — and then the pivot: 'the LORD declares to you that the LORD will make you a house.' The wordplay is pointed: David wanted to make YHWH a house (<em>bayit</em>); instead, YHWH will make David a house — i.e., a dynasty (<em>bayit</em> = both physical structure and lineage). The divine reversal of the gift-direction is the structural heart of the covenant: YHWH is the giver, not the receiver of the decisive benefaction. Matt 11:28-30 applies the rest-promise directly to Christ: 'Come to me... and I will give you rest' — Christ claiming the YHWH-role in the rest-giving formula of 2 Sam 7:11.</p>",
    "12": "<p>A direct prophecy: 'When your days are over and you rest with your ancestors, I will raise up your offspring to succeed you, who will come from your own body, and I will establish his kingdom.' Acts 13:22-23 cites this oracle directly for Jesus: 'of this man's offspring God has brought to Israel a Savior, Jesus, as he promised.' The promise has two fulfillments: a near-term one in Solomon (who builds the Temple) and an ultimate one in Christ (whose kingdom is eternal, v.16). Paul's use in Acts 13 establishes the citation as the foundational NT proof-text for Jesus as the Davidic heir.</p>",
    "13": "<p>A direct prophecy with dual fulfillment: 'He will build a house for my name, and I will establish the throne of his kingdom forever.' Solomon fulfills the first clause (building the Temple); the second — 'forever' (<em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em>) — exceeds any historical fulfillment, pointing to the eternal Davidic king. John 2:19-21 makes Christ's claim explicit: 'Destroy this temple, and in three days I will raise it up' — his body is the true temple. 1 Cor 3:16-17 extends this: the church is the temple of God in Christ. The house built 'for YHWH's name' is realized not in stone but in the body of Christ and his community.</p>",
    "14": "<p>A direct prophecy, explicitly cited in the NT: 'I will be his father, and he will be my son.' Heb 1:5 quotes this verse as the primary OT basis for Jesus's unique divine sonship: 'For to which of the angels did God ever say, You are my Son, I will be to you a father?' The quotation establishes that 2 Sam 7:14 is the OT's founding text for the father-son relationship between YHWH and the Davidic king — which the NT claims is uniquely and definitively realized in Christ. The disciplinary clause — 'when he does wrong, I will discipline him with the rod of men' — applies to Solomon, not to the ultimate fulfillment; Hebrews applies the discipline-theme to Jesus's suffering (Heb 5:8: 'although he was a son, he learned obedience through what he suffered').</p>",
    "15": "<p>The contrast with Saul is the key clause: 'my steadfast love (<em>ḥesed</em>) will not be taken from him, as I took it from Saul, whom I removed before you.' The permanence of the Davidic covenant is established by explicit contrast with Saul's conditional and withdrawn favor. The <em>ḥesed</em> YHWH pledges to the Davidic line is <em>permanent</em> — not conditioned on the individual king's obedience but secured by the divine oath. Ps 89:28-29 develops this: 'my steadfast love I will keep for him forever, and my covenant will stand firm for him.' The NT fulfillment is the unbreakable nature of Christ's covenant: 'he holds his priesthood permanently, because he continues forever' (Heb 7:24).</p>",
    "16": "<p>The eternal covenant: 'Your house and your kingdom will endure before me forever, and your throne will be established forever.' <em>ʿad-ʿôlām</em> (forever) appears twice in this verse — the double emphasis on the eternal, unending character of the Davidic dynasty. Luke 1:32-33 cites this promise directly in the annunciation: 'the Lord God will give to him the throne of his father David, and he will reign over the house of Jacob forever, and of his kingdom there will be no end.' The eternal throne promised to David's line is the direct textual basis for the NT's claim about Christ's eternal kingship. This verse, more than any other, is the hinge between the OT messianic promise and the NT announcement of Christ.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Nathan's complete transmission of the oracle to David — 'Nathan spoke to David all these words and shared with him the whole of this vision' — confirms the prophetic fidelity required: the full oracle, not a selection, is transmitted. As a theme: the faithful prophet transmits the complete word of YHWH, not edited for palatability. This is the standard the NT applies to apostolic preaching: Paul declares 'the whole counsel of God' (Acts 20:27) and refuses to preach 'a different gospel' (Gal 1:8).</p>",
    "18": "<p>David's prayer of response opens with profound humility: 'Who am I, Lord God, and what is my family, that you have brought me this far?' The two questions — about personal identity and familial lineage — acknowledge that there is nothing in David or his house that warrants this covenant. As a theme: the Davidic covenant is entirely gracious, grounded in YHWH's initiative, not David's merit. This posture of unworthy-recipient-of-grace is the OT model for the NT's theology of grace: 'it is by grace you have been saved through faith — and this is not your own doing; it is the gift of God' (Eph 2:8).</p>",
    "19": "<p>David's wonder at the scope of the promise: 'and yet this was too small a thing in your eyes, Lord God; you have also spoken about your servant's house for a great while to come.' The phrase 'a great while to come' (<em>lᵉmērāḥôq</em>, into the distant future) points beyond the immediate to the eschatological dimension of the promise. As a revelation of God: YHWH's generosity exceeds the recipient's expectation — the promise is larger than David could imagine. This is the OT basis for Paul's doxology in Eph 3:20: 'to him who is able to do far more abundantly than all we ask or think.'</p>",
    "20": "<p>'What more can David say to you? You know your servant, Lord God.' The acknowledgment of YHWH's comprehensive knowledge — 'you know' — is a posture of transparency before the omniscient God. This is the OT's preparation for Christ's statement in John 10:14 ('I know my own and my own know me') and for the NT's picture of the believer fully known by God (1 Cor 13:12: 'then I shall know fully, even as I have been fully known').</p>",
    "21": "<p>'For the sake of your servant and according to your own purpose, you have done all these great things.' The phrase <em>biʿᵃḇûr dāḇᵉrᵉḵā</em> — 'according to your own word/purpose' — locates the origin of the covenant entirely in YHWH's own resolve, not David's initiative. As a revelation of God: the great things done are done 'according to his own purpose and grace' (2 Tim 1:9) — the same formula Paul uses for the eternal election that underlies the gospel.</p>",
    "22": "<p>'Therefore you are great, LORD God. There is no one like you, and there is no God besides you.' David's theological summary of the covenant is a statement of YHWH's uniqueness — the incomparability of the God who makes and keeps such promises. The formula 'there is no God besides you' (<em>ʾên ʾĕlōhîm zûlāteḵā</em>) is the Shema extended into prayer: the covenant is the act of the one God who has no rival. As a revelation of God: the Davidic covenant is the specific, historical expression of the exclusive lordship that the NT claims Christ uniquely mediates (1 Cor 8:6: 'one God, the Father... and one Lord, Jesus Christ').</p>",
    "23": "<p>'And who is like your people Israel, the one nation on earth whom God went to redeem as his own people?' — the covenant people as the object of a unique divine rescue mission. The language of 'redemption' (<em>lᵉpāḏôt</em>, to ransom) is used for YHWH's action in the Exodus and here applied to the people's ongoing identity. The NT extends the 'redeemed people' concept to the church: 'a people for his own possession' (1 Pet 2:9; Tit 2:14) — the Davidic covenant creates a community whose identity is constituted by YHWH's rescue, precisely fulfilled in Christ's cross.</p>",
    "24": "<p>'You established Israel as your people forever, and you, LORD, have become their God.' The double covenant formula — 'they shall be my people and I will be their God' — is the central covenant declaration running from Exod 6:7 through Jer 31:33 to Rev 21:3 ('they will be his people, and God himself will be with them as their God'). David's prayer here sets this formula within the Davidic covenant: the eternal kingship and the eternal covenant-relationship belong together. Christ's fulfillment encompasses both: the new covenant in his blood (Luke 22:20) and his eternal reign (Rev 11:15) are the same event.</p>",
    "25": "<p>'And now, LORD God, confirm forever the word you have spoken about your servant and his house.' David's prayer is not an act of doubt but of faith claiming the promise — 'do as you have spoken.' The same pattern governs NT prayer: 'your will be done' and 'confirm the good word you have spoken.' As a theme: prayer in the Davidic covenant is the act of holding YHWH to his own word — the grounds for confidence is not human faithfulness but divine promise. The same logic undergirds Heb 6:17-18: YHWH confirmed his promise 'by an oath, so that by two unchangeable things, in which it is impossible for God to lie, we who have fled for refuge might have strong encouragement.'</p>",
    "26": "<p>'May your name be magnified forever.' The prayer for YHWH's name — not David's name — to be exalted through the Davidic covenant is the right ordering of covenant purpose. The Davidic dynasty exists for YHWH's glory, not its own. As a theme: the eschatological purpose of the Davidic covenant is YHWH's name being magnified 'forever' — which the NT presents as the purpose of Christ's kingship: 'so that at the name of Jesus every knee should bow... and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord, to the glory of God the Father' (Phil 2:10-11).</p>",
    "27": "<p>'For you, LORD of hosts, God of Israel, have revealed this to your servant: I will build you a house.' The revelation is the ground of the request: David prays for what YHWH has already promised because the promise is the authorization for the prayer. As a theme: prayer within the covenant is always the claiming of what has been promised — not petition into the unknown but faith responding to revealed intention. The NT makes this explicit in 1 John 5:14-15: 'if we ask anything according to his will, he hears us.'</p>",
    "28": "<p>'Now, Lord God, you are God; your words are true, and you have made this good promise to your servant.' The acknowledgment that YHWH's words are 'true' (<em>ʾĕmet</em>) is not merely an epistemological claim but a covenantal one: YHWH is the God whose character is reliable, whose word can be trusted as the foundation for prayer and life. As a revelation of God: the trustworthiness of the divine word is what makes the Davidic covenant livable — and the NT fulfillment is precisely Christ as 'the yes and amen to all God's promises' (2 Cor 1:20).</p>",
    "29": "<p>'Therefore be pleased to bless the house of your servant, so that it may stand before you forever.' The prayer ends with a request for the permanence of what YHWH has promised. The closing formula — 'for you, Lord God, have spoken, and with your blessing the house of your servant will be blessed forever' — grounds the eternal blessing entirely in the divine word and the divine blessing, not in anything David or his house provides. As a revelation of God: the eternal blessing flows from YHWH's own word. The NT conclusion to this trajectory is Heb 13:20-21: 'the God of peace, who brought again from the dead our Lord Jesus, the great shepherd of the sheep, by the blood of the eternal covenant, equip you with everything good that you may do his will' — the eternal covenant's blessing, secured by the Davidic Son's resurrection.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-christ', '2samuel')
    merge_comm(existing, SAMUEL2)
    save_comm('mkt-christ', '2samuel', existing)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in SAMUEL2.values())
    print(f'2 Samuel 4–7 mkt-christ: wrote {count} verses across ch 4-7')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
